<DOC><DOCNO> AP890423-0038 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-04-23-89 1341EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-Czechoslovakia-Activists     04-23 0182</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Czechoslovakia-Activists,0188</SECOND><HEAD>Three Activists Detained Prior To Planned Meeting With Hungarians</HEAD><DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Three prominent Czechoslovak activistswere detained Sunday on their way to meet Hungarian activists inthe Czechoslovak city of Bratislava, emigre sources said.   Petr Uhl, Jan Urban and Petr Pospichal, all leading members ofthe Charter 77 human rights group, were planning to meetindependent Hungarian activists at Bratislava's Carlton Hotel, theLondon-based emigre publisher Palach Press reported.   Anna Sabatova, Uhl's wife, said the three were picked up bypolice as they got off the train from Prague.   She said they were to meet three Hungarian activists. Two weremembers of the Hungarian independent youth group, and third was theHungarian representative of an independent East Europeaninformation agency formed in December by activists from Poland,Czechoslovakia, Hungary and the Soviet Union.   Uhl, Pospichal and Urban are the Czechoslovak representatives ofthe same group.   On Friday, four Czechoslovak activists, including former ForeignMinister Jiri Hajek, were prevented by police from traveling toWarsaw where they had planned to take part in an internationalhuman rights symposium.</TEXT></DOC>